Importing citations from PubMed into RefWorks
Answer: •	To send items to RefWorks, please do the following:  o	Select the PubMed citations that you’d like to export  o	Click on “Send to:”  o	Select “Citation manager” and create and save the file to a convenient location    o	In RefWorks, hover over References and then select “Import”  o	Select NLM PubMed as your Import Filter/Data Source  o	The database will automatically change to PubMed  o	Select the file that you downloaded using the “Browse” option  o	Select the folder that you’d like to import using the “Import into Folder” option (this is an optional, but time-saving step)  o	Voila!  You should have successfully imported your references.

Question: I have had problems accessing the databases recently. When I go to articles and databases and choose nutrition; when I choose the majority of the databases I get the message A System Problem has Occurred  To begin a new session, please login again with underneath the logo of EBSCO host.  I use to find a lot of articles in the main search screen of the library but apparently the interface changed and it almost always bring me back to this EBSCO screen!  I use the on line chat but they could not help...  I have to find an research article from Jean Mayer (1920-1993) who wrote more than 750 articles and can't find one...I am kind of frustrated....  What do you think I should do?  Thank you in advance
Answer: I checked PubMed and found some articles for you....    Here's what I would recommend you do:    1) Go to the library's homepage > Articles & Databases > P > PubMed  2) On PubMed's page, click on the Single Citation Matcher link  3) For Author, input Mayer J (select it from the auto-suggested list)  4) Click on search  5) You will get 2,244 results  6) Restrict by selecting English and adding AND hunger to the search box (this is what you should have Mayer J[author] AND hunger) -- Note, I just put in hunger.
